1. Cancelling this event in light of recent events would have been cowardly, and I doubt anyone even actually wanted that, despite Dean Tomiko Brown-Nagin's insistence that some folks requested that. (21/n)

The event is now over. Prof. Hammonds remarked that the event was recorded, and that a recording of the event will be made available on Radcliffe's website within the week. I have a lot of thoughts about this whole thing, and here are three: (20/n)

@clancynewyork Thanks! I was planning on attending this event anyway, as a student of Prof. Hill's and an (until-very-recently) ardent admirers of Prof. Hammonds'. It occurred to me once the topic came up that others might want to hear what Prof. Hammonds had to say.

As questions continue to come in, it seems unlikely that the conversation will be turned back to recent events, unless by the choice of the Professors involved. If it does, I will update this thread. (19/n)

The first question that seems inspired by recent events has come through the Q&A. It addresses Title IX as a flawed process. Professor Hammonds asks the question without commentary, Professor Hill answers. (18/n)

(15/n)
As this conversation between Drs. Anita Hill and Evelynn Hammonds, we move to Q&A. This session can be watched live on YouTube here: https://t.co/0JgbDEonmX (14/n)

"...I have long been familiar with the destructive power of gender-based violence, and I still have a lot more to learn. I know that this conversation will give us all the opportunity to do so." (13/n)

"...that I completely support them and I applaud their enormous courage in bringing their charges forward and making these charges known to us all. I can think of no better time to be in the conversation with you about this..." (12/n)

"...I truly regret signing the letter. This has been a difficult, soul-searching moment for me. After receiving additional information, I retracted my name from the statement. I want to say that I absolutely stand with the students in this case and I want to state..." (11/n)

"...with respect to very important and essential processes. The letter has been read as supporting -- accusing -- supporting the accused, questioning the veracity of the students who brought forth the charges. That was never what I intended..." (10/n)

"...that had been followed with respect to sexual harassment charges brought against one of my colleagues. So, my intent in signing the letter was to merely draw attention to very particular issues - what I believed, at the time, was a lack of transparency..." (9/n)

"... These are the very issues that you have addressed in your new book. So I just want to make a couple of points, as a member of the faculty of arts and sciences. I signed a letter, earlier this week, that I believed raised a number of questions about the procedures..." (8/n)

Professor Hammonds states: "I am so excited about this conversation, but I want to begin, before we get to questions, to acknowledge that we are in the midst of a controversy roiling the Harvard campus, as Dean [Tomiko] Brown-Nagin [who introduced both speakers] said..." (7/n)

Professor Hammonds addresses her recent decision to join 37 other professors and sign a letter published in the Harvard Crimson criticizing the process through which Harvard Anthropology professor John Comaroff was adjudicated for allegations of sexual harrassment. (6/n)
Before the question-and-answer portion of the evening (during which the chat function is disabled, and attendees are unable to submit questions anonymously)... (5/n)

Dr. Hill says that Mamet missed the most important issue of sexual assault and harassment on college campuses, being "how college structures work together to silence victims, often sweeping incidents and complaints under the rug." (4/n)

Discussing David Mamet's play OLEANNA, Dr. Hill writes, "We are meant to believe that a student armed with words alone can shift the balance of power to her side, which we are also led to believe is dangerous." (3/n)

The conversation, which is with Professor Anita Hill of Brandeis University, focuses on Dr. Hill's book BELIEVING, which (among many other things) examines "the structural balance of power" and its role in gender-based violence. (2/n)

I should add that reports of Japan's laws applying to Olympic athletes, and more specifically to Simone Biles, have not Ben confirmed by her or by the Olympic Committee. This thread was simply my explanation of how very real methylphenidate withdrawal is, in light of speculation. https://t.co/rMQ2FcHP24
My thoughts about #SimoneBiles and any other #Olympics athletes being forced to perform without their medication. https://t.co/btrGIw1FiI
I'm not a gymnast, and I've never gotten the "twisties", but from descriptions I've read, every day without my medication feels like that, and I wouldn't wish it on anyone.

I honestly don't know how any Olympic athlete with ADHD is dealing with the withdrawal and still competing, but as someone who ALSO has trauma related to sexual assault, I wouldn't wish both at the same time on anyone, much less Simone Biles.
I wouldn't do a single cartwheel on a foam floor on a day I haven't taken my medication, let alone fling myself through the air at high speeds (if that were something I knew how to do).

I don't make appointments or talk to people unless I absolutely have to. I don't drive if I can help it. I have gone to work before on a medication-less day, but I've never been able to finish a full shift as planned on one.

even sitting down and watching a movie or an episode of TV becomes impossible. my focus is completely scrambled. I've compared my handwriting on and off my meds, and it's honestly hard to tell it's the same person.

My brain feels like it is in a fog, and I have trouble concentrating on any task for more than a few minutes. I lose my train of thought, and have even been known to simply walk out of the room in the middle of a conversation.
I am hungry all day. I take 3-4 naps and still rest for a full 8 hours at night. I get headaches, nausea, and GI distress. These are just the physical symptoms.

going cold-turkey off of your meds is a struggle for a lot of different reasons, and it's doubtless physically and mentally difficult to suddenly be without something your body has come to rely on. That said, I have never felt anything like methylphenidate withdrawal.
one time I unexpectedly didn't have my methylphenidate for five days, and by the third day I was physically incapable of maintaining a train of thought for more than 90 seconds at a time.
